clinical_study.brief_title: Single vs Double Epidural Catheter Analgesia for Scoliosis Surgery
clinical_study.official_title: Single Versus Double Epidural Catheter Technique for Postoperative Analgesia Following Scoliosis Surgery

brief_summary.textblock: This is a study comparing pain control utlilizing one or two epidural catheters, along with a hydromorphone PCA, for analgesia following surgery for correction of scoliosis.

clinical_study.why_stopped: Study was unable to meet patient enrollment goals. PI chose to terminate the study early.

primary_outcome.description: The pain scores will be examined using the Numeric Rating Scale (NRS). NRS score ranges from 0-10. Higher score represents more pain/worse outcome

secondary_outcome.description: The pain scores will be examined using the Numeric Rating Scale (NRS). NRS score ranges from 0-10. Higher score represents more pain/worse outcome
Hydromorphone usage measured in mcg/kg/day. No min/max. More hydromorphone usage represents worse outcome

secondary_outcome.measure: Functional Outcomes:The Pediatric Outcomes Data Collection Instrument (PODCI) Score
secondary_outcome.description: Functional outcome will be measured by the Pediatric Outcomes Data Collection Instrument (PODCI). Scores range from 0-100, lower score represents higher degree of disability

secondary_outcome.measure: Functional Outcomes: Scoliosis Research Society-22r (SRS-22r) Patient Questionnaire
secondary_outcome.description: Functional outcome will be measured by the Scoliosis Research Society-22r (SRS-22r). Scores range from 0-110, higher scores represent less disability/better outcome

secondary_outcome.measure: Functional Outcomes: The Owestry Disability Index(ODI)
secondary_outcome.description: Functional outcome will be measured by the Owestry Disability Index (ODI). ODI represents following disability levels: 0% -20%: Minimal disability, 21%-40%: Moderate Disability, 41%-60%: Severe Disability, 61%-80%: Crippling back pain, 81%-100%: These patients are either bed-bound or have an exaggeration of their symptoms.

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion Criteria:
1. Patients undergoing surgery via a posterior approach for AIS
2. Children ages 11-18
3. ASA physical status 1-2
4. Informed consent by legal guardian and assent by patient (for minors 11-17 years of age) or informed consent by subject (for patients 18 years of age)
5. Planned correction of at least 8 vertebral levels
Exclusion Criteria:
1. Patient refusal to participate
2. Patients on chronic narcotic medication
3. Allergy to standard of care drugs used in the study (Omnipaque, ropivacaine, hydromorphone, oxycodone, acetaminophen, gabapentin, ondansetron, nalbuphine or diphenhydramine, diazepam)
4. Coagulopathy
5. Pre-existing neurological deficit
6. Inability to use a Numerical Rating Scale (NRS: 0-10 patient self-reported score) for pain assessment
